Data Parsing and Merging¶

We will define a function that will parse an individual raw JSON data file coming from the Accuweather API.

An important aspect with this API is how we handle dates and times. Note that AccuWeather provides forecasts at different times per hour, so we will round each date to the nearest hour. Also, since we want to compare equivalent times in different location, we strip the time zone information.

In [5]:
def round_datetime(obs_date):
    # round and convert to a Pandas TimeStamp
    ts = pd.Timestamp(obs_date)
    return ts.round(freq="H")
In [6]:
def parse_raw_data(city_name, fpath):
    fin = open(fpath, "r")
    jdata = fin.read()
    data = json.loads(jdata)
    # handle each observation
    rows = []
    for obs in data:
        row = {"City": city_name}
        # parse the local datatime in ISO8601 format
        obs_date = datetime.strptime(obs["LocalObservationDateTime"], "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S%z")
        # strip the timezone
        obs_date = obs_date.replace(tzinfo=None)
        # round it to the nearest hour
        row["Date"] = round_datetime(obs_date)
        # add temperature data, in celsius - both raw and 'feels like' with wind chill
        row["Temperature"] = obs["ApparentTemperature"]["Metric"]["Value"]
        row["WindChillTemperature"] = obs["WindChillTemperature"]["Metric"]["Value"]
        # add precpipation level, in mm for last hour
        row["PrecipitationLevel"] = obs["Precip1hr"]["Metric"]["Value"]
        # add wind speed
        row["Wind"] = obs["Wind"]["Speed"]["Metric"]["Value"]
        # add relative humidity
        row["Humidity"] = obs["RelativeHumidity"]
        # add cloud cover, as a float representing percentage
        row["CloudCover"] = float(obs["CloudCover"])/100
        # add other fields
        row["Description"] = obs["WeatherText"]
        rows.append(row)
    fin.close()
    # return back the DataFrame
    return pd.DataFrame(rows)

Define a function that will parse and merge a collection of raw data files:

In [7]:
def parse_merge_raw_data(city_name, fpaths):
    df_files = []
    # process each file for this city
    print("Reading and parsing %d JSON data files ..." % len(fpaths))
    for fpath in fpaths:
        # produce a DataFrame from this file
        df_file = parse_raw_data(city_name, fpath)
        df_files.append(df_file)
    # concatenate all the DataFrames together into a single frame
    df_city = pd.concat(df_files)
    # next we remove duplicate observations based on the Date field
    df_city.drop_duplicates(subset="Date", keep="first", inplace=True)
    # now set the index column to be the Date, which is now unique
    df_city.set_index("Date", inplace=True)
    # we will also sort the frame by its index
    return df_city.sort_index()

def summarize_dates():
    rows = []
    for city_name in city_names:
        row = {"City": city_name}
        row["Rows"] = len(df_cities[city_name])
        row["DateStart"] = df_cities[city_name].index.min()
        row["DateEnd"] = df_cities[city_name].index.max()
        rows.append(row)
    return pd.DataFrame(rows).set_index("City")

Temperature Analysis¶

First we will look at temperature data. We could just look at the raw statistics for the different cities. We'll create function to do this, so that we can reuse it later.

In [17]:
def compute_stats(col_name):
    rows = []
    for city_name in city_names:
        row = {"City": city_name}
        row["Min"] = df_cities[city_name][col_name].min()
        row["Max"] = df_cities[city_name][col_name].max()
        row["Mean"] = df_cities[city_name][col_name].mean()
        row["Median"] = df_cities[city_name][col_name].median()
        rows.append(row)
    return pd.DataFrame(rows).set_index("City")

df_daily_temps = {}
for city_name in city_names:
    # groupy each index by day
    groups = df_cities[city_name]["Temperature"].groupby(pd.Grouper(freq='D'))
    min_temps = groups.min()
    max_temps = groups.max()
    # combine the min and max daily values into a new DataFrame
    df_daily_temps[city_name] = pd.DataFrame({"Min": min_temps, "Max": max_temps})

Alternatively, to analyse temperatures we could merge the data from the different cities into a single DataFrame. Again we'll create a convenience function for this so that we can re-use it later.

In [22]:
def merge_data_by_column(col_name):
    columns = {}
    for city_name in city_names:
        columns[city_name] = df_cities[city_name][col_name]
    df_merged = pd.DataFrame(columns).sort_index()
    # note if we have some mismatches on dates between cities, we will drop the rows
    return df_merged.dropna()

In [33]:
# set a very low threshold
precipitation_threshold = 0.1
city_rainy_hours = {}
for city_name in city_names:
    precip = df_cities[city_name]["PrecipitationLevel"]
    # how many rows reach the threshold?
    num_rainy = len(precip[precip>=precipitation_threshold])
    # convert number to percentage
    city_rainy_hours[city_name] = (100.0*num_rainy)/len(precip)
# convert to a Series
rainy_hours = pd.Series(city_rainy_hours)

Overall, we can see from the above that Dublin had a far higher percentage of hours where at least some rain fell, while Lisbon had very few hours were any rain fell at all.

We could use a more nuanced classification of rain intensity, as described here:

  • Light rain when the precipitation level is < 2.5 mm per hour
  • Moderate rain when the precipitation level is between 2.5 to 7.6 mm per hour
  • Heavy rain when the precipitation level is > 7.6 mm per hour
In [35]:
rows = []
# create a DataFrame with hourly percentage for different rainfall categories
for city_name in city_names:
    row = {"Light":0, "Moderate":0, "Heavy":0}
    for i, value in df_cities[city_name]["PrecipitationLevel"].iteritems():
        if value > 7.6:
            row["Heavy"] += 1
        elif value >= 2.5:
            row["Moderate"] += 1
        # any rain at all?
        elif value > 0.1:
            row["Light"] += 1
    # convert numbers to percentages
    for key in row:
        row[key] = (100.0*row[key])/len(df_cities[city_name])
    row["City"] = city_name
    rows.append(row)
df_rain_levels = pd.DataFrame(rows).set_index("City")
# put the cities on columns
df_rain_levels = df_rain_levels.transpose()
df_rain_levels

Again could also look at the percentage of "windy hours" per city across all of the observations for each city, based on some threshold.

We could for instance, consider "windy" to be anything to be Force 5 "Fresh breeze" and above on the The Beaufort Scale, which starts at 29km/h:

https://www.met.ie/forecasts/marine-inland-lakes/beaufort-scale

In [41]:
wind_speed__threshold = 29
city_windy_hours = {}
for city_name in city_names:
    precip = df_cities[city_name]["Wind"]
    # how many rows reach the threshold?
    num_windy = len(precip[precip>=wind_speed__threshold])
    # convert number to percentage
    city_windy_hours[city_name] = (100.0*num_windy)/len(precip)
# convert to a Series
windy_hours = pd.Series(city_windy_hours)

Correlations Between Cities¶

Next, we will look at the extent to which the different cities are correlated with one another, under different weather variables. We'll use the merge DataFrames that we created earlier.

We will define a single fuction which computes the pairwise Pearson correlations between the columns (i.e. cities) and displays this as a 'heatmap' visualisation:

In [43]:
import numpy as np
def plot_heatmap(title, df_in, figsize=(5.5, 5)):
    df_corr = df_in.corr()
    # create a color palettte
    cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
    # display the heatmap
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(df_corr, square=True, cbar=False,
                annot=True, cmap=cmap, linewidths=0.5, vmin=-1)
    ax.set_title(title)

First, look at the correlation heatmap for temperature:

In [44]:
plot_heatmap("Temperature Correlations", df_temp_merged)

In terms of temperature correlations, we can see a reasonable level of correlation between Dublin and London, and less so for Lisbon. The correlation between Rome and the other cities is considerably lower.

We could also look at precipitation level:

In [45]:
plot_heatmap("Precipitation Level Correlations", df_precip_merged)

In this case the correlations across cities are far lower, with a few negative correlations.

Or we could look at another variable, such as percentage cloud cover:

In [46]:

Again, we see little relation between the cloud cover values across the four cities.

We could view these values for the weather descriptions as providing a numeric profile or set of features for describing the weather in each of these cities.

We could measure the similarity or distance between these profiles, using a standard measure such as Euclidean distance:

From these distance values, for each city we could find the most similar (least distant) and least similar (most distant) other city:

In [57]:
print("-- Weather profiles")
for i, city_name in enumerate(city_names):
    dmin, dmax = 0, 0
    city_min, city_max = None, None
    for j in range(len(city_names)):
        # skip the diagonal
        if i == j:
            continue
        if city_min is None or D[i,j] < dmin:
            dmin = D[i,j]
            city_min = city_names[j]
        if city_max is None or D[i,j] > dmax:
            dmax = D[i,j]
            city_max = city_names[j]  
    print("%s\t Most similar to %s, least similar to %s" % (city_name, city_min, city_max))

-- Weather profiles
Dublin	 Most similar to London, least similar to Lisbon
Lisbon	 Most similar to Rome, least similar to Dublin
London	 Most similar to Dublin, least similar to Lisbon
Rome	 Most similar to Lisbon, least similar to Dublin

As we might expect, the profiles for Dublin and London are most similar to one another, with the other two more southerly cities are more similar (both sometimes referred to as having warm-temperate Mediterranean climates).

Conclusions¶

In this assignment we looked at the analysis of hourly data for four locations, focusing particularly on temperature, precipitation, and wind speeds. As we might expect, the weather patterns for Dublin and London were similar to some extent, and certainly Dublin experienced quite different conditions from Rome and Lisbon during the time period that we studied.

One particular challenge of using the free AccuWeather API is that historic data only covers the previous 24 hour period, which meant that the data collection process had to be repeated many times to build up an initial raw dataset. A considerable level of data preprocessing was also required to merge the raw data into a single dataset for each city.

A number of interesting avenues could be considered for further analysis of this data:

  • The analysis could be extended to a larger number of cities to further investigated the idea of 'weather profiles' based on text descriptions.
  • If further historic data was available, we could consider whether the weather observed in our data was in line with seasonal norms.
  • Again if we had further historic data, we could experiment with time series forecasting methods to attempt to make predictions for variables like hourly temperature.
